ERules about charges for the supply of water in bulk
	The Authority may issue rules about charges that may be imposed by a waterundertaker under a bulk supply agreement.
	The rules may in particular make provision about—
		what types of charge may be imposed;
		the amount or the maximum amount, or a method for determining the amount ormaximum amount, of any type of charge;
		principles for determining what types of charge may or may not be imposed;
		principles for determining the amount of any charge that may be imposed;
		publication of the charges that may be imposed.
	If the Authority considers that a water undertaker is not acting asrequired by rules under this section, the Authority may give the undertaker adirection to do, or not to do, a particular thing specified in the direction.
	It is the duty of a water undertaker to comply with a direction undersubsection (3), and this duty is enforceable by the Authority under section18.
	The rules may—
		make different provision for different water undertakers or differentdescriptions of water undertaker;
		make different provision for different purposes;
		make provision subject to exceptions.
	The Authority may from time to time revise rules issued under this sectionand issue revised rules.
	The Authority must issue revised rules if—
		guidance is issued under section 40I, and
		the Authority, having regard to that guidance, considers that it isappropriate to revise the rules.
	Revised rules may include provision for applying any of their revisions tobulk supply agreements made before the revised rules come into effect.

FRules under section 40E: provision about the reduction of charges
	Rules under section 40E may provide for the reduction of charges payablefor a supply of water under a bulk supply agreement where conditions specifiedby the rules are satisfied.
	Rules made by virtue of subsection (1) may in particular—
		specify conditions that affect any party to a bulk supply agreement;
		require that steps be taken for the purpose of reducing or managing waterconsumption;
		specify conditions about reducing charges payable by a person who—
		is not party to the agreement, and
		takes or proposes to take such steps as satisfy or would satisfy acondition falling within paragraph (b).
	The rules may provide that, where a charge falls to be reduced inaccordance with rules made by virtue of subsection (1), the water undertakerto which the charges are payable must give notice of that reduction to theAuthority.
	Rules made by virtue of subsection (3) may—
		make provision as to the content of the notice;
		specify the period within which an undertaker is to give notice to theAuthority.
	Provision under subsection (4)(a) may in particular require the notice tospecify—
		the provision of the rules that brings about the reduction in the charge;
		the amount of the charge, with and without the reduction;
		the period for which the reduction has effect.

CCodes in respect of main connection agreements
	The Authority may issue one or more codes in respect of main connectionagreements.
	A code may make provision about—
		procedures in connection with making an agreement to permit a mainconnection into a sewerage undertaker’s sewerage system;
		procedures in connection with varying or terminating a main connectionagreement;
		procedures to be followed by the Authority in determining whether to makean order under section 110A(3) or 110B(1);
		the terms and conditions of a main connection agreement, including terms asto the duration of such an agreement;
		principles for determining the terms and conditions that should or shouldnot be incorporated into a main connection agreement;
		the steps to be taken by the Authority in determining whether a person iscomplying with the code.
	If the Authority considers that a sewerage undertaker is not acting asrequired by a code, the Authority may give the undertaker a direction to do,or not to do, a particular thing specified in the direction.
	The Authority may not give a direction under subsection (3) requiring aperson to enter into, vary or terminate an agreement.
	It is the duty of a sewerage undertaker to comply with a direction undersubsection (3), and this duty is enforceable by the Authority under section18.
	A code may make different provision for different persons or differentdescriptions of person.
	The Authority may from time to time revise a code issued under this sectionand issue a revised code.
	A revised code may include provision for applying any of its revisions tomain connection agreements made before the revised code comes into force.

FRules about charges for permitting main connections
	The Authority may issue rules about charges that may be imposed by asewerage undertaker under a main connection agreement.
	The rules may in particular make provision about—
		what types of charge may be imposed;
		the amount or the maximum amount, or a method for determining the amount ormaximum amount, of any type of charge;
		principles for determining what types of charge may or may not be imposed;
		principles for determining the amount of any charge that may be imposed;
		publication of the charges that may be imposed.
	If the Authority considers that a sewerage undertaker is not acting asrequired by rules under this section, the Authority may give the undertaker adirection to do, or not to do, a particular thing specified in the direction.
	It is the duty of a sewerage undertaker to comply with a direction undersubsection (3), and this duty is enforceable by the Authority under section18.
	The rules may—
		make different provision for different sewerage undertakers or differentdescriptions of sewerage undertaker;
		make different provision for different purposes;
		make provision subject to exceptions.
	The Authority may from time to time revise rules issued under this sectionand issue revised rules.
	The Authority must issue revised rules if—
		guidance is issued under section 110J, and
		the Authority, having regard to that guidance, considers that it isappropriate to revise the rules.
	Revised rules may include provision for applying any of the revisions tomain connection agreements made before the revised rules come into effect.

GRules under section 110F: provision about the reduction of charges
	Rules under section 110F may provide for the reduction of charges payableunder a main connection agreement where conditions specified by the rules aresatisfied.
	Rules made by virtue of subsection (1) may in particular—
		specify conditions by reference to any party to a main connectionagreement;
		require that steps be taken for the purpose of reducing the cost to asewerage undertaker of permitting a main connection into its sewerage system;
		specify conditions about reducing charges payable by a person who—
		is not party to the agreement, and
		takes or proposes to take such steps as satisfy or would satisfy acondition falling within paragraph (b).
	The rules may provide that, where a charge falls to be reduced inaccordance with rules made by virtue of subsection (1), the sewerageundertaker to which the charges are payable must give notice of that reductionto the Authority.
	Rules made by virtue of subsection (3) may—
		make provision as to the content of the notice;
		specify the period within which an undertaker is to give notice to theAuthority.
	Provision under subsection (4)(a) may in particular require the notice tospecify—
		the provision of the rules that brings about the reduction in the charge;
		the amount of the charge, with and without the reduction;
		the period for which the reduction has effect.

CACodes in respect of section 51A agreements
	The Authority must issue a code in respect of section 51A agreements.
	The code may make provision about—
		procedures in connection with making an agreement under section 51A;
		procedures in connection with varying or terminating a section 51Aagreement;
		procedures to be followed by the Authority in determining whether to makean order under section 51B(4) or 51C(1);
		the circumstances in which it is, or is not, appropriate for work to bedone by a person other than a water undertaker;
		the terms and conditions of a section 51A agreement;
		principles for determining the terms and conditions that should or shouldnot be incorporated into a section 51A agreement;
		the steps to be taken by the Authority in determining whether a person iscomplying with the code.
	Provision under subsection (2)(c) may in particular require the Authorityto consult—
		the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water;
		the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water for Wales if there is one.
	Provision under subsection (2)(d) may include in particular provision aboutcircumstances relating to—
		the nature of the work;
		the kind of premises supplied or to be supplied.
	Provision under subsection (2)(e) may include in particular provision aboutterms and conditions as regards—
		constructing associated infrastructure;
		vesting associated infrastructure in a water undertaker;
		constructing water mains so as to meet additional supply requirements;
		connecting new water mains or service pipes to the existing supply systemof a water undertaker;
		complying with requirements of the kind referred to in section 47(2);
		the duration of a section 51A agreement.
	If the Authority considers that a water undertaker is not acting asrequired by the code, the Authority may give the undertaker a direction to do,or not to do, a particular thing specified in the direction.
	The Authority may not give a direction under subsection (6) requiring aperson to enter into, vary or terminate an agreement.
	It is the duty of a water undertaker to comply with a direction undersubsection (6), and this duty is enforceable by the Authority under section18.
	The code may make different provision for different persons or descriptionsof person.
	The Authority must from time to time review the code and, if appropriate,issue a revised code.
	A revised code may include provision for applying any of its revisions tosection 51A agreements made before the revised code comes into force.

ZCCodes in respect of section 104 agreements
	The Authority must issue a code in respect of section 104 agreements.
	The code may make provision about—
		procedures in connection with making an agreement under section 104;
		procedures in connection with varying or terminating a section 104agreement;
		procedures to be followed by the Authority in determining whether to makean order under section 105ZA(4) or 105ZB(1);
		the circumstances in which it is, or is not, appropriate for work to bedone by a person other than a sewerage undertaker;
		the terms and conditions of a section 104 agreement;
		principles for determining the terms and conditions that should or shouldnot be incorporated into a section 104 agreement;
		the steps to be taken by the Authority in determining whether a person iscomplying with the code.
	Provision under subsection (2)(d) may include in particular provision aboutcircumstances relating to—
		the nature of the work;
		the kind of premises supplied or to be supplied.
	Provision under subsection (2)(e) may include in particular provision aboutterms and conditions as regards—
		constructing associated infrastructure;
		vesting associated infrastructure in a sewerage undertaker;
		making a communication with public sewers.
	If the Authority considers that a sewerage undertaker is not acting asrequired by the code, the Authority may give the undertaker a direction to do,or not to do, a particular thing specified in the direction.
	The Authority may not give a direction under subsection (5) requiring aperson to enter into, vary or terminate an agreement.
	It is the duty of a sewerage undertaker to comply with a direction undersubsection (5), and this duty is enforceable by the Authority under section18.
	The code may make different provision for different persons or descriptionsof person.
	The Authority must from time to time review the code and, if appropriate,issue a revised code.
	A revised code may include provision for applying any of its revisions tosection 104 agreements made before the revised code comes into force.

Appointments and variations
	Procedure with respect to appointments and variations
		Section 8 of the Water Industry Act 1991 (procedure with respect toappointments and variations replacing relevant undertakers) is amended asfollows.
		In subsection (2)(a) (the Water Services Regulation Authority to servenotice of application), for “on the existing appointee the NRA and on every”there is substituted “on—
			the existing appointee,
			if the application relates to the replacement of a water undertaker whosearea is wholly or mainly in England, the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water,
			if the application relates to the replacement of a water undertaker whosearea is wholly or mainly in Wales, the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water forWales if there is one, or the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water if section86(1B)(b) applies,
			the appropriate agency, and
			every”. 
		In subsection (4)(b) (the Secretary of State or the Water ServicesRegulation Authority to serve notice of proposed appointment or variation),for “on the existing appointee the NRA and on every” there is substituted “on—
			the existing appointee,
			if the proposed appointment or variation would replace a water undertakerwhose area is wholly or mainly in England, the Chief Inspector of DrinkingWater,
			if the proposed appointment or variation would replace a water undertakerwhose area is wholly or mainly in Wales, the Chief Inspector of Drinking Waterfor Wales if there is one, or the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water if section86(1B)(b) applies,
			the appropriate agency, and
			every”. 
		In subsection (5)(b) (the Secretary of State or the Water ServicesRegulation Authority to serve notice of the making of an appointment orvariation), for “on the NRA and on every” there is substituted “on—
			if the appointment or variation replaces a water undertaker whose area iswholly or mainly in England, the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water,
			if the appointment or variation replaces a water undertaker whose area iswholly or mainly in Wales, the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water for Wales ifthere is one, or the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water if section 86(1B)(b)applies,
			the appropriate agency, and
			every”. 
		After subsection (6) insert—
			“(6A)In this section “the appropriate agency”, in relation to the replacementof a relevant undertaker, means—
			the Environment Agency, if the undertaker’s area is wholly in England;
			the NRBW, if the undertaker’s area is wholly in Wales;
			both the Environment Agency and the NRBW, if the undertaker’s area ispartly in England and partly in Wales.”

Charges for providing a water main etc
	The Water Industry Act 1991 is amended as follows.
	In section 42 (financial conditions for compliance with the duty in section41 to provide a water main)—
		in subsection (1)(b) (condition as to providing security), for the wordsfrom “such security” to “reasonably required” there is substituted “suchsecurity as charging rules allow and the undertaker may have required”;
		in subsection (2) (undertaking to pay), for paragraph (a) there issubstituted—
		bind the person or persons mentioned in that subsection to pay to theundertaker such charges as the undertaker may impose in accordance withcharging rules, and”;
		subsections (4) and (5) (interest on sums deposited by way of security) arerepealed;
		in subsection (6) (reference of disputes to Water Services RegulationAuthority), in paragraph (b), after “the amount” there is inserted “or amountsby way of charges”.
	In section 45 (duty to make domestic connections to a water main)—
		in subsection (2) (the nature of the duty), the words “, at the expense ofthe person serving the notice,” are repealed;
		for subsection (6) there is substituted—
	Where a water undertaker carries out any works which it is its duty underthis section to carry out, the person serving the notice is liable to pay tothe undertaker such charges as the undertaker may impose in accordance withcharging rules.”;
		in subsection (6A) (reference of disputes to Authority), for “as to whetherthe expenses were incurred reasonably” there is substituted “as to thepayments required to be made”.
	In section 46 (duty to carry out ancillary works for the purpose of makinga domestic connection under section 45)—
		in subsection (1) (the nature of the duty), the words “, at the expense ofthe person serving the notice,” are repealed;
		in subsection (7), in paragraph (b), for “under this section at anotherperson’s expense” there is substituted “as its duty under this section”;
		in subsection (7), in the words after paragraph (b), for “under thatsection at another person’s expense” there is substituted “as its duty underthat section”;
		in subsection (9) (consequences of exercising power under section 46(8) tolay a water main rather than a service pipe), paragraph (b) (maximum expensesrecoverable) and the “but” preceding it are repealed.
	In section 47 (conditions of connection with water main)—
		in subsection (2)(a) (requirement to give security for amounts to be paid),for the words from “such security” to “reasonably require” there issubstituted “such security as charging rules allow and the undertakerrequires”;
		in subsection (3B) (reference of disputes to Authority), in the openingwords, “whether” is repealed;
		in subsection (3B), for paragraph (a) there is substituted—
		the security required to be provided by a condition imposed undersubsection (2)(a),”;
		in subsection (3B)(b), at the beginning there is inserted “whether”;
		in subsection (3B)(c), after “particular case,” there is inserted“whether”.

Charges for providing a public sewer etc
	The Water Industry Act 1991 is amended as follows.
	In section 99 (financial conditions for compliance with the duty in section98 to provide a public sewer or lateral drain)—
		in subsection (1)(b) (condition as to providing security), for the wordsfrom “such security” to “reasonably required” there is substituted “suchsecurity as charging rules allow and the undertaker may have required”;
		in subsection (2) (undertaking to pay in respect of public sewer), forparagraph (a) there is substituted—
		bind the person or persons mentioned in that subsection to pay to theundertaker such charges as the undertaker may impose in accordance withcharging rules, and”;
		in subsection (2A) (undertaking to pay in respect of lateral drain), forparagraph (a) there is substituted—
		bind the person or persons mentioned in that subsection to pay to theundertaker such charges as the undertaker may impose in accordance withcharging rules, and”;
		subsections (4) and (5) (interest on sums deposited by way of security) arerepealed;
		in subsection (6) (reference of disputes to the Water Services RegulationAuthority), in paragraph (b), after “the amount” there is inserted “or amountsby way of charges”.
	In section 101B (power to provide lateral drain following provision ofpublic sewer)—
		in subsection (3) (obligation to pay for drain requested), for “the costsreasonably incurred in or in connection with providing that drain” there issubstituted “such charges as the undertaker may impose in accordance withcharging rules”;
		after subsection (3) there is inserted—
			“(3A)The sewerage undertaker may require the person making a request underthis section to provide such security for the payment of the charges ascharging rules allow.”;
		in subsection (4) (reference of disputes to Authority), for paragraph (b)there is substituted—
		the amount of any charge imposed,”;
		in subsection (4), after paragraph (b) there is inserted “or
		the security required to be provided,”.
	In section 107 (right of a sewerage undertaker to undertake the making of acommunication with a public sewer)—
		in subsection (3)(b)(i) (no obligation for undertaker to act until paid anestimated cost of the work in advance), for “the cost of the work” there issubstituted “the amount by way of charges that the undertaker may impose inaccordance with charging rules for making the connection”;
		in subsection (3)(b)(ii) (no obligation for undertaker to act until givensecurity for payment), for “such security” to the end there is substituted“such security for the payment of that amount as charging rules allow and itmay have required.”;
		for subsection (4), there is substituted—
	If a payment to a sewerage undertaker under subsection (3) exceeds thecharges that may, in the event, be imposed in accordance with charging rulesfor making the connection in question, the excess is to be repaid by theundertaker; and, if and so far as those charges are not covered by a paymentunder subsection (3), those charges are to be paid by the person for whom thework was undertaken.”;
		in subsection (4A) (reference to disputes to Authority), in paragraph (a),for “of the cost of works” there is substituted “of the amount of charges”;
		in subsection (4A), for paragraph (b) (and the “or” following it) there issubstituted—
		the security required by the undertaker, or”;
		in subsection (4A), for paragraph (c) there is substituted—
		whether any excess is repayable, or any charges are payable, undersubsection (4), or the amount of any such excess or charges,”.
	In section 146 (connection charges etc, and charges for highway drainage),in subsection (5)(a), after “expenses incurred by it in” there is inserted “,or charges imposed by it for,”.

Register relating to undertakers and licensees
	Section 195 of the Water Industry Act 1991 (the Water Services RegulationAuthority’s register relating to undertakers and licensees) is amended asfollows.
	In subsection (1) (register to be maintained in a certain place, in acertain form and for certain purposes), the words from “for the purposes” tothe end are repealed.
	After subsection (3C) (inserted by section 33) there is inserted—
		“(3D)Subject to any direction given under subsection (3), the Authority mustcause to be entered on the register the provisions of—
		a notice under section 40F(3) (reduction in charges payable under a bulksupply agreement);
		a notice under section 66EA(3) (reduction in charges payable under asection 66D agreement);
		a notice under section 110G(3) (reduction in charges payable under a mainconnection agreement);
		a notice under section 117J(3) (reduction in charges payable under asection 117E agreement).”

Adjudication functions
	Exercise of adjudication functions by other persons
		After section 207C of the Water Industry Act 1991 (inserted by section 37)there is inserted—
		“Adjudication
		DExercise of adjudication functions by other persons
			The Minister may by order made by statutory instrument provide that any ofthe Authority’s adjudication functions (see subsection (4)) is to beexercised—
				on the Authority’s behalf, by such person as may be specified in the order,or
				either by the Authority or, on the Authority’s behalf, by such person asmay be specified in the order, at the option of the Authority in anyparticular case.
			An order under subsection (1) may—
				provide for requirements applying to the exercise of a function by theAuthority to apply to the exercise of the function by another person;
				require the Authority to produce guidance as to the exercise by anotherperson of one of the Authority’s adjudication functions and to keep suchguidance up to date;
				require a person exercising one of the Authority’s adjudication functionsto have regard to—
				any guidance to which the Authority would have regard in exercising thatfunction;
				any guidance produced by the Authority as to the exercise of thatfunction.
			An order under subsection (1) may—
				make different provision for different purposes;
				apply any primary or secondary legislation with or without modifications;
				make supplemental, consequential and transitional provision.
			For the purposes of this section, the Authority’s adjudication functionsare—
				the determination of any matter referred to it for determination undersection 30A;
				the Authority’s functions under any of the following—
					  * regulations made by virtue of section 38(4) (power to prescribe by regulations standards of performance for water undertakers as regards water supply in individual cases: provision for disputes etc);
					  * regulations made by virtue of section 38ZA(4) (power to prescribe by regulations standards of performance for water supply licensees as regards water supply in individual cases: provision for disputes etc);
					  * regulations made by virtue of section 95(4) (power to prescribe by regulations standards of performance for sewerage undertakers as regards sewerage services in individual cases: provision for disputes etc);
					  * regulations made by virtue of section 95ZA(4) (power to prescribe by regulations standards of performance for sewerage licensees as regards sewerage services in individual cases: provision for disputes etc);
					  * section 105 (appeals with respect to adoption of sewer etc);
					  * section 105B (appeals relating to schemes for the adoption of sewers etc);
					  * section 110 (determination of disputes with respect to cross boundary sewers);
					  * section 112(2) and (3) (appeal against requirement that proposed drain or sewer be constructed so as to form part of general system);
					  * section 122 (appeals relating to applications to discharge trade effluent);
					  * section 126 (appeals with respect to variations of consent to discharge trade effluent);
					  * section 128 (application for variation of time for discharge of trade effluent);
					  * section 181 (investigation of complaints with respect to the exercise of works powers on private land);
					but do not include any functions as to enforcement under section 18.
			In this section—
				  * “the Minister”, in relation to an adjudication function of the Authority, means—
				the Secretary of State, to the extent that the function is to be exercised—
				in relation to a relevant undertaker whose area is wholly or mainly inEngland,
				in relation to a water supply licensee using the supply system of such anundertaker (see section 17B), or
				in relation to a sewerage licensee using the sewerage system of such anundertaker (see section 17BA);
				the Welsh Ministers, to the extent that the function is to be exercised—
				in relation to a relevant undertaker whose area is wholly or mainly in Wales,or
				in relation to a water supply licensee using the supply system of such anundertaker (see section 17B);
					  * “primary legislation” means an Act or an Act or Measure of the Assembly;
					  * “secondary legislation” means an instrument made under primary legislation.
			A statutory instrument containing an order made by the Secretary of Stateunder this section may not be made unless a draft of the instrument has beenlaid before, and approved by a resolution of, each House of Parliament.
			A statutory instrument containing an order made by the Welsh Ministersunder this section may not be made unless a draft of the instrument has beenlaid before, and approved by a resolution of, the Assembly.”

Application for retail exit
	Exit regulations about exit applications must make provision requiring arelevant undertaker to apply to the Secretary of State, and may include—
		provision requiring a relevant undertaker to take such steps as theregulations may specify before making an application;
		provision as to the form and manner in which an application is to be madeand as to the contents of an application;
		provision about payment to the Secretary of State of a fee of an amountspecified in or determined under the regulations;
		provision about the information that is to accompany an application;
		provision for the Secretary of State to require a relevant undertaker toprovide such further information as the Secretary of State may require inorder to make a determination;
		provision as to the grounds on which an application may be refused;
		provision for the Secretary of State to grant an application subject toconditions.
	Provision under subsection (1)(a) may require a relevant undertaker—
		to consult—
		its non-household customers and its other customers,
		the WSRA,
		the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water,
		the Consumer Council for Water, and
		any other person specified in the regulations;
		to prepare and publish a report assessing the effect on non-householdcustomers and other customers if the undertaker withdraws from the non-household retail market;
		to publish notice of its proposed exit application in such manner as theregulations may specify.
	The grounds that may be specified under subsection (1)(f) include—
		grounds relating to the public interest or to the interests of a section ofthe public;
		grounds relating to the interests of non-household customers or othercustomers;
		grounds relating to costs associated with a transfer of part of therelevant undertaker’s undertaking;
		grounds relating to the eligible licensee or licensees to which a transferof part of the relevant undertaker’s undertaking is proposed to be made.
	The conditions that may be imposed under subsection (1)(g) include—
		conditions as to the persons who are to pay the costs associated with atransfer of a part of the relevant undertaker’s undertaking;
		conditions as to the application of money received by the relevantundertaker in connection with a transfer of a part of its undertaking;
		conditions about the relevant undertaker giving consent to modifications ofthe undertaker’s conditions of appointment;
		conditions about an eligible licensee to which a transfer of part of therelevant undertaker’s undertaking is proposed to be made giving consent tomodifications of the conditions of its water supply licence or seweragelicence;
		conditions about the treatment of non-household customers affected by thetransfer of part of the relevant undertaker’s undertaking.
	Exit regulations may make provision about how particular descriptions ofcustomers and premises are affected by a relevant undertaker’s withdrawal fromthe non-household retail market, including in particular any of the following—
		premises to which the supply of water has been disconnected,
		premises that are to be demolished,
		premises that are temporarily unoccupied,
		premises in relation to which the owner or occupier has served notice undersection 63AA of the Water Industry Act 1991 (supply by water supply licensee:domestic supply),
		premises in relation to which the owner or occupier has served notice undersection 63AB of the Water Industry Act 1991 (supply by water supply licensee:non-domestic supply), and
		premises in relation to which the owner or occupier has served notice undersection 110K of the Water Industry Act 1991 (provision by sewerage licensee).
	Provision under subsection (5) may include provision about how exitapplications deal with particular descriptions of customers and premises.
	Exit regulations may make provision about the disclosure by a relevantundertaker of such information as the regulations may specify about—
		its non-household customers, and
		the charges payable by them (whether payable under a charges scheme undersection 143 of the Water Industry Act 1991 or under an agreement).
	Exit regulations may specify—
		the persons to whom the information may be disclosed;
		the purposes for which it may be disclosed.

Transfer of undertaking
	Exit regulations about the transfer of a part of a relevant undertaker’sundertaking may include provision for the making of a scheme to transferproperty, rights and liabilities where an exit application has been granted.
	Exit regulations about the transfer of a part of a relevant undertaker’sundertaking may include provision about arrangements under Chapter 1 of Part 5of the Water Industry Act 1991 for fixing, demanding and recovering charges.
	Provision under subsection (2) may include—
		provision for and in connection with treating such arrangements as if theywere agreements between the undertaker and the person liable to pay suchcharges;
		provision about the terms and conditions of such agreements.
	Exit regulations may make provision for a scheme under subsection (1) tocontain—
		provision identifying the property, rights and liabilities to betransferred (which may include property, rights and liabilities that would nototherwise be capable of being transferred);
		provision for the division of property, rights and liabilities, including—
		provision creating an interest in or right over property;
		provision creating new rights and liabilities;
		incidental provision as to the property, rights and liabilities of otherpersons;
		provision about the consideration to be provided (and about the enforcementof such provision).
	Subsection (4) is not exhaustive of what a scheme may contain.

Operation of retail market: charges etc
	Exit regulations may make provision for water supply licensees and seweragelicensees, that are providing or proposing to provide services under theirwater supply or sewerage licences in relation to a retail exit area, to make,and from time to time revise, a scheme containing the terms and conditionswhich, in the absence of agreed terms and conditions, are to apply to suchservices.
	Provision under subsection (1) may include—
		provision for a scheme to make different provision for different purposes,or different areas;
		provision about the publication of a scheme or revised scheme;
		provision about sending a copy of a scheme or revised scheme to the WSRA;
		provision enabling the WSRA to direct that terms or conditions be modifiedgenerally or in a particular case;
		provision requiring a licensee to comply with a direction under paragraph(d), including provision for enforcing such a duty under section 18 of theWater Industry Act 1991.
	Provision under subsection (1) may also include—
		provision requiring the WSRA to issue a code about providing services towhich a scheme under subsection (1) relates;
		provision for the code to include, in particular, provision about—
		the terms and conditions contained in such schemes;
		licensees informing owners or occupiers of premises about their schemesbefore agreeing any terms and conditions for the provision of services;
		provision for the WSRA, if it considers that a licensee is not acting asrequired by such provision as is described in paragraph (b), to give thelicensee a direction to do, or not to do, a particular thing specified in thedirection;
		provision requiring a licensee to comply with a direction under paragraph(c), including provision for enforcing such a duty under section 18 of theWater Industry Act 1991;
		provision requiring the WSRA from time to time to review the code and, ifappropriate, to issue a revised code.
	Exit regulations may make provision for the WSRA to issue and enforce—
		rules about charges for services that may be imposed by water supply orsewerage licensees in relation to a retail exit area;
		if exit regulations make provision for licensees to make schemes about suchcharges, rules about such schemes.
	Provision under subsection (4) may include—
		provision for the rules to make different provision for different cases;
		provision for the WSRA to direct a licensee to comply with the rules;
		provision for such directions to be enforceable by the WSRA under section18;
		provision for the Secretary of State to issue guidance as to the content ofthe rules;
		provision for the Secretary of State to prevent rules being issued.

Exit regulations: general
	Exit regulations may make such provision as the Secretary of Stateconsiders appropriate—
		for modifying a person’s duties and powers, and
		for imposing new duties and conferring new powers on a person.
	The persons in relation to whom provision under subsection (1) may be madeinclude—
		the Secretary of State;
		the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water;
		the Welsh Ministers;
		the Chief Inspector of Drinking Water for Wales if there is one, or theChief Inspector of Drinking Water if section 86(1B)(b) of the Water IndustryAct 1991 applies;
		the WSRA;
		the CMA;
		the Environment Agency;
		the NRBW;
		the Consumer Council for Water;
		relevant undertakers;
		water supply licensees and sewerage licensees.
	Exit regulations may—
		apply enactments, with or without such modifications as the Secretary ofState thinks fit;
		amend, repeal or revoke enactments.
	The provision that may be made by exit regulations includes provisionconferring power to make subordinate legislation.
	Exit regulations may—
		contain such consequential, incidental, supplementary, transitional orsaving provisions (including provisions amending, repealing or revokingenactments) as the Secretary of State considers appropriate, and
		make different provision for different cases, including different provisionin relation to different persons, circumstances or areas.
	In this section “enactment”—
		includes an Act or Measure of the National Assembly for Wales;
		includes an enactment contained in this Act, other than this Chapter.

Interpretation 
	In this Chapter—
		  * “the CMA” means the Competition and Markets Authority; 
		  * “eligible licensee” has the meaning given by section 44; 
		  * “exit application” means an application under section 42(1)(a); 
		  * “the NRBW” means the Natural Resources Body for Wales; 
		  * “non-household customer” means a person who is the customer as regards a service provided in respect of non-household premises; 
		  * “non-household premises” means premises other than household premises as defined in section 17C of the Water Industry Act 1991; 
		  * “retail exit area” has the meaning given by section 42; 
		  * “the WSRA” means the Water Services Regulation Authority. 
	Except in so far as the context otherwise requires, terms used in thisChapter have the same meaning as in the Water Industry Act 1991.

Procedure 
	Before making exit regulations, the Secretary of State is to consult—
		the Welsh Ministers;
		the WSRA;
		the CMA;
		the Consumer Council for Water;
		relevant undertakers whose areas are wholly or mainly in England;
		water supply licensees and sewerage licensees;
		persons whom the Secretary of State considers to represent the interests ofinvestors in the water industry.
	The power to make exit regulations is to be exercised by statutoryinstrument.
	A statutory instrument containing exit regulations made by the Secretary ofState may not be made unless a draft of the instrument has been laid before,and approved by a resolution of, each House of Parliament.

Information 
	The Secretary of State may by regulations make provision about—
		the provision of information, and
		the production of documents,
			by insurers for the purposes of regulations under section 70.
	The regulations may in particular require an insurer to provide informationof a prescribed description or produce documents of a prescribed descriptionfor the purpose of showing, in relation to a prescribed period—
		whether or not an insurer is a relevant insurer;
		whether or not an exemption applies (see section 70(5)(b)).
	The regulations may in particular require an insurer to provide informationor produce documents about—
		the insurance policies issued by it in a prescribed period that providecover against prescribed descriptions of risk;
		the value of the insurance policies so issued;
		insurance policies so issued that do not remain in force to the end of theperiod of cover;
		the value of such insurance policies.
	The regulations may provide for information to be provided or documents tobe produced to the Secretary of State or a person acting on behalf of theSecretary of State.
	The regulations may make provision—
		about the time within which information must be provided or documentsproduced;
		about the form in which information is to be provided;
		about the place where documents are to be produced;
		requiring information to be verified in a prescribed manner;
		requiring documents to be authenticated in a prescribed manner.
	The regulations may make provision about—
		the persons to whom, and the purposes for which, information supplied by aninsurer may be disclosed;
		the publication of information by the Secretary of State about the amountof insurance business of a prescribed description done by insurers, takentogether.
	In this section “prescribed” means specified in or determined in accordancewith regulations under this section.

Section 72: further provision
	The Secretary of State may by regulations make provision for and inconnection with enforcing compliance with obligations imposed by regulationsunder section 72.
	The regulations may in particular include—
		provision about the sanctions, including civil penalties, that may beimposed by the Secretary of State or a person acting on behalf of theSecretary of State for non-compliance with the obligations;
		provision about the procedure to be followed when imposing a sanction;
		provision about the recovery of costs incurred in connection with imposinga sanction up to the time of its imposition;
		provision enabling an appeal to the First-tier Tribunal against theimposition of a sanction or a requirement to pay costs.
	Provision under subsection (2)(a) may in particular include—
		provision for civil penalties of a fixed amount;
		provision for further amounts to be payable by way of civil penalty wherean insurer continues to fail to comply with the obligation in question;
		provision about how a civil penalty or an amount of costs may be recovered.
	Provision under subsection (2)(d) may include provision as to the groundson which an appeal may be made.

Register of premises subject to greater flood risk
	The Secretary of State may by regulations provide for the creation andmaintenance of a register of household premises in the United Kingdom that aresubject to greater flood risk for the purposes of regulations under section70.
	The regulations may provide for the levels of flood risk to which premisesare subject to be divided into two or more bands (“risk bands”), and mayprescribe the upper and lower limits of each band.
	The regulations may provide for the register to specify the level of floodrisk to which particular household premises are subject by specifying the riskband applicable to the premises.
	The regulations may provide for premises of a description specified in theregulations to be excluded from the register, and the premises excluded mayinclude in particular premises where construction is completed on or after adate specified in the regulations.
	The regulations may—
		specify the information to be contained in the register;
		make provision about access to the information contained in the register;
		provide for the publication of the register in whole or in part;
		provide for the disclosure of information contained in the register;
		provide for notification if premises are entered in, or omitted from, theregister.
	Regulations made under subsection (5)(d) may provide for—
		the persons to whom information or any description of information containedin the register may be disclosed;
		the imposition of conditions on persons to whom information contained inthe register is disclosed, including conditions limiting further disclosure;
		penalties for non-compliance with conditions imposed under paragraph (b).
	The regulations may require applications for premises to be entered in theregister to be made by or on behalf of a person who has the qualifyinginterest in the premises.
	The regulations may provide for premises to be omitted from the register atthe request of a person who has the qualifying interest in the premises.
	Before making regulations under this section the Secretary of State mustconsult—
		the Welsh Ministers;
		the Scottish Ministers;
		the Department of Agriculture and Rural Development in Northern Ireland.

Functions of relevant bodies
	Regulations under section 74 may provide for a relevant body to carry outfunctions in connection with—
		the creation and maintenance of the register;
		giving access to information contained in the register;
		publication of the register;
		disclosure of information contained in the register;
		notification when premises are entered in, or omitted from, the register.
	The following are relevant bodies for the purposes of this Part—
		the Environment Agency;
		the Scottish Environment Protection Agency, in relation to Scotland;
		the Natural Resources Body for Wales, in relation to Wales;
		the Department of Agriculture and Rural Development in Northern Ireland, inrelation to Northern Ireland.
	The regulations may provide for the Environment Agency—
		to coordinate the carrying out of functions conferred or imposed undersubsection (1);
		to promote consistency in the carrying out of those functions.
	The regulations may—
		require the relevant bodies to cooperate with each other as regards thefunctions conferred or imposed on any of them under subsection (1);
		require the relevant bodies (other than the Environment Agency) tocooperate with the Environment Agency as regards the carrying out of functionsconferred or imposed on the Environment Agency under subsection (3).
	Regulations under section 74 may provide for the Commissioners for HerMajesty’s Revenue and Customs, or a person authorised by them, to discloseinformation held for council tax purposes by the Valuation Office to—
		the Environment Agency, or
		the Natural Resources Body for Wales,
			for use in identifying premises to be excluded from the register by referenceto the date of completion of construction (see section 74(4)).
	The regulations may include provision restricting the use or furtherdisclosure of information disclosed under subsection (5).

Functions of the FCA
	The Treasury may by regulations provide for the FCA to take action formonitoring and enforcing compliance with—
		such of the obligations imposed on relevant insurers by regulations undersection 70 or 78 as may be specified in the regulations;
		such description of those obligations as may be specified in theregulations.
	The regulations may provide for the FCA to take action for enforcingcompliance with—
		such of the obligations imposed on insurers by regulations under section 72as may be specified in the regulations;
		such description of those obligations as may be specified in theregulations.
	Regulations under subsection (2) may only provide for the FCA to takeaction as regards cases where—
		the failure to comply, if proved, would consist in or involve providinginformation that is not true or producing a document that is not correct, or
		measures available under section 73 have been taken without securingcompliance.
	The regulations may apply, or make provision corresponding to, any of theprovisions of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 or the FinancialServices Act 2012, with or without modification.
	The provisions of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 and theFinancial Services Act 2012 referred to in subsection (4) include inparticular—
		provisions about gathering information and investigating, includingprovisions as to powers of entry and search;
		provisions as to criminal offences and disciplinary measures;
		provisions for the grant of an injunction in relation to a contravention oranticipated contravention;
		provisions giving the Treasury or the FCA powers to make subordinatelegislation;
		provisions for the FCA to charge fees;
		provisions restricting liability in damages in relation to the discharge offunctions of the FCA.
	The regulations may make provision enabling the FCA, to such extent as theregulations may prescribe, to make arrangements for the performance offunctions on its behalf.

Reports by the FCA
	The Treasury may by regulations provide for the FCA to prepare reports onits discharge of the functions conferred on it under section 79.
	The regulations may—
		make provision about the contents of the reports;
		make provision about the timing of the reports;
		provide for copies of the report to be given to the Secretary of State andsuch other persons as the regulations may specify;
		provide for publication of the reports.

Intervention by the FCA or the PRA
	The Treasury may by regulations confer on a regulator the power to disapplyor modify, in relation to a relevant insurer, an obligation imposed byregulations under—
		section 70 (flood insurance obligations),
		section 72 (information), or
		section 78 (compliance reports).
	In this section “the intervention power” means the power conferred byregulations under subsection (1).
	The regulations may specify which obligations, or which descriptions ofobligations, a regulator may disapply or modify under the intervention power.
	The regulations may specify what modifications, or what descriptions ofmodifications, may be made by a regulator under the intervention power.
	The regulations may specify the circumstances in which, and the conditionssubject to which, a regulator may exercise the intervention power.
	Provision under subsection (5) may in particular provide for a regulator toexercise the intervention power in relation to a relevant insurer—
		where the relevant insurer is failing, or is likely to fail, to satisfy thethreshold conditions for which the regulator is responsible,
		in connection with advancing—
		if the regulator is the FCA, one or more of the FCA’s operationalobjectives, or
		if the regulator is the PRA, one or more of the PRA’s objectives,
		in conjunction with the exercise by the regulator, in respect of therelevant insurer, of a power that is conferred on the regulator by or under anenactment and is specified in the regulations, or
		at the request of, or for the purpose of assisting, an overseas regulatorof a kind specified in the regulations.
	The regulations may—
		make provision about the procedure to be followed when exercising theintervention power, including provision about consulting such persons as maybe specified in the regulations about a proposed exercise of the power;
		make provision requiring a regulator to give a relevant insurer notice inwriting specifying how the intervention power has been exercised in relationto that relevant insurer;
		make provision about when an exercise of the intervention power takeseffect;
		make provision about the period for which a provision of regulations may bedisapplied or modified under the intervention power, including—
		provision enabling a regulator to specify the period for which a provisionof regulations is disapplied or modified;
		provision for disapplying or modifying a provision of regulations until aregulator provides for it to apply again or to apply again withoutmodification;
		make provision requiring a regulator—
		to send copies of a notice under paragraph (b) to the Secretary of Stateand such other persons as may be specified in the regulations;
		to notify such persons as may be specified in the regulations of theexercise of the intervention power;
		make provision requiring a regulator to publish such details about theexercise of the intervention power as may be specified in the regulations;
		make provision requiring a regulator to keep under review each case inwhich a provision of regulations is disapplied or modified;
		make provision about the matters to which a regulator is to have regard inexercising its functions under the regulations.
	Provision under subsection (7)(e) or (f) may allow for the omission ofinformation publication of which would in the opinion of the regulator beagainst the public interest.
	The intervention power may be exercised in respect of an obligation imposedby regulations under section 70(1) only so as to disapply the obligation (andnot so as to modify it).
	The regulations may apply, or make provision corresponding to, any of theprovisions of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 or the FinancialServices Act 2012, with or without modification.
	The provisions of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 or theFinancial Services Act 2012 referred to in subsection (10) include inparticular—
		provisions about gathering information and investigating, includingprovisions as to powers of entry and search;
		provisions as to criminal offences and disciplinary measures;
		provisions for the grant of an injunction in relation to a contravention oranticipated contravention;
		provisions giving the Treasury, the FCA or the PRA powers to makesubordinate legislation;
		provisions for the FCA or the PRA to charge fees;
		provisions restricting liability in damages in relation to the discharge offunctions of the FCA or the PRA.
	In this section “regulator” means the FCA or the PRA.
	For— 
		  * “objective of the PRA”, see section 2F of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000; 
		  * “operational objective of the FCA”, see section 1B(3) of that Act; 
		  * “overseas regulator”, see section 55Q of that Act; 
		  * “threshold condition”, see section 55B of that Act.

Part 6General and final
	Power to make consequential provision
		The Secretary of State may by order made by statutory instrument make suchprovision as the Secretary of State considers appropriate in consequence ofthis Act.
		The power conferred by subsection (1) includes power—
			to make transitional, transitory or saving provision;
			to amend, repeal, revoke or otherwise modify any provision made by or underan enactment (whenever passed or made).
		A statutory instrument containing (whether alone or with other provision)an order under this section which amends or repeals any provision of an Act ofParliament, or of an Act or Measure of the National Assembly for Wales, is notto be made unless a draft of the instrument has been laid before, and approvedby a resolution of, each House of Parliament.
		A statutory instrument containing any other order under this section issubject to annulment in pursuance of a resolution of either House ofParliament.
	Transitional, transitory or saving provision
		The Secretary of State may by order made by statutory instrument make suchtransitional, transitory or saving provision as the Secretary of Stateconsiders appropriate in connection with the coming into force of anyprovision of this Act.
		Subsection (1) does not apply if or to the extent that subsection (3) or(4) applies.
		If a provision of this Act is brought into force to any extent by the WelshMinisters acting alone under section 94(3), the Welsh Ministers may by ordermade by statutory instrument make such transitional, transitory or savingprovision as the Welsh Ministers consider appropriate in connection with thecoming into force of so much of that provision as is so brought into force.
		If a provision of this Act is brought into force to any extent by theSecretary of State and the Welsh Ministers acting jointly under section 94(3),the Secretary of State and the Welsh Ministers may, acting jointly, by ordermade by statutory instrument make such transitional, transitory or savingprovision as they, together, consider appropriate in connection with thecoming into force of so much of that provision as is so brought into force.
		Schedule 11 (further provision about orders under this section) has effect.
	Financial provisions
		There shall be paid out of money provided by Parliament—
			expenditure incurred under or by virtue of this Act by the Secretary ofState;
			any increase attributable to this Act in the sums payable under any otherAct out of money so provided.
	Extent 
		This Act extends to England and Wales only, subject as follows.
		Sections 61 and 62 and Schedule 8 extend also to Scotland, but only so faras required for the purposes of regulations applying as mentioned in section61(11)(b).
		Part 4 and this Part extend to England and Wales, Scotland and NorthernIreland.
		An amendment or repeal made by this Act has the same extent as theenactment to which it relates.
